text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!Dative presentatives in Kentucky English and derivatives%0a%0a:Author: TimG%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHere's you a short article on dative presentatives%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe presentative, as discussed in the Yale article (1), is the "Here" in the sentence "Here is the pizza." The idea is to present something to a participant in the conversation. The dative is a pronoun or pronoun phrase. Thus, the dative presentative looks something like this: "Here's you the whole pizza," specifically denoting the person being presented the pizza.%0a%0aThe dative can be first, second, or third person, as well as an actual name, although not every speaker of a dialect which accepts some of these datives after the presentative accepts all of them. It can be used in questions as well, such as "Where's me a pizza," which is a very good question. The Yale database suggests that this language construction is most readily accepted in the American South, where the Kentucky dialect of English was most likely to spread.%0a%0a1. https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/dative-presentatives%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210424-035944-956340#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!More Examples of Presentatives - and their uses in verbs %0a-> - nithyas%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAs mentioned in your article, the use of the presentative is common in many Southern dialects of American English. As someone from a region where these dialects are common, I found it interesting that while the dative presentative is not as common in my regional dialects, the addition of the dative to a verb instead is much more common.%0a%0aFor example, phrase construction like, "I love me some country music" or "I need to get me some new shoes" are common.%0a%0aThe article you linked also  mentions that this kind of construction is largely rejected in the North, and even to me, a sentence like "Here’s him a nice cup of coffee" sounds a little strange. One way to think about it, however, is the dative presentative is just a different syntax for a preposition. For example, "Here’s him a nice cup of coffee" is meant to convey "Here’s a nice cup of coffee for him", which would be considered more grammatical by most people.%0a%0aHere are some more examples of the dative: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/personal-datives%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210424-035944-956340#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
