diff:1619236783:1618100224:=49,63c49%0a%3c #foxbegin 210424-035944-956340#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!More Examples of Presentatives - and their uses in verbs %0a%3c -> - nithyas%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c As mentioned in your article, the use of the presentative is common in many Southern dialects of American English. As someone from a region where these dialects are common, I found it interesting that while the dative presentative is not as common in my regional dialects, the addition of the dative to a verb instead is much more common.
%0a%3c 
%0a%3c For example, phrase construction like, "I love me some country music" or "I need to get me some new shoes" are common.
%0a%3c 
%0a%3c The article you linked also  mentions that this kind of construction is largely rejected in the North, and even to me, a sentence like "Here’s him a nice cup of coffee" sounds a little strange. One way to think about it, however, is the dative presentative is just a different syntax for a preposition. For example, "Here’s him a nice cup of coffee" is meant to convey "Here’s a nice cup of coffee for him", which would be considered more grammatical by most people.
%0a%3c 
%0a%3c Here are some more examples of the dative: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/personal-datives%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210424-035944-956340#%0a---%0a> %0a
