diff:1618100224:1618100224:=1,71d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Dative presentatives in Kentucky English and derivatives%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: TimG%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Here's you a short article on dative presentatives%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c The presentative, as discussed in the Yale article (1), is the "Here" in the sentence "Here is the pizza." The idea is to present something to a participant in the conversation. The dative is a pronoun or pronoun phrase. Thus, the dative presentative looks something like this: "Here's you the whole pizza," specifically denoting the person being presented the pizza.
%0a%3c 
%0a%3c The dative can be first, second, or third person, as well as an actual name, although not every speaker of a dialect which accepts some of these datives after the presentative accepts all of them. It can be used in questions as well, such as "Where's me a pizza," which is a very good question. The Yale database suggests that this language construction is most readily accepted in the American South, where the Kentucky dialect of English was most likely to spread.
%0a%3c  
